		<p class="prose">If you’re old enough, this sounds like quintessential 2000s/2010s emo: <b>Dashboard Confessional's</b> <a href="http://www.rookiemag.com/2015/07/where-the-girls-arent/">sensitive heart</a>, but over a hip hop beat. Some call it emo-rap, an emerging hip hop sub-genre. But this song’s lyrics feel just as emotionally vulnerable as Dashboard, the poster band of mid-2000s teenage angst.
		</p>
		<p class="prose">I wondered: <b>who has the most emotionally vulnerable lyrics, emo-rappers or Dashboard Confessional?</b> Has Juice Wrld out-emo’d emo bands?
		</p>
		<div class="explanation">
			<div class="left-col">
				<p class="prose">I used the same calculation that identified <a href="http://www.rcharlie.com/post/fitter-happier/">Radiohead’s saddest track</a>: the percent of each songs’s words associated with an emotion of <span class="sad-word">sad</span> or <span class="sad-word">fear</span> (my proxy for “emo” lyrics).
				</p>
				<p class="prose">For example, here’s the chorus of Lil Uzi Vert’s “XO Tour Llif3.” <b>33%</b> of the words are in the sad/fear list, which all things considered is pretty emo-rich.
				</p>
				<p class="prose small-text">*we remove common words that generally don’t evoke meaning, i.e., stop words
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="right-col">
